<P>1. The Plaintiff claims as against the Defendants, Yao Jun Situ and Yao Feng Situ:
<P1>(a) payment of the amount of $630,352.21 due under covenants contained in a Mortgage plus any additional expenses, charges and costs, incurred or to be incurred by the Plaintiff in respect of the said mortgage;</P1>
<P1>(b) possession of the lands as set out in Schedule &ldquo;A&rdquo;;</P1>
<P1>(c) interest at the rate of 14.5% per annum from November 26, 2018 to the date of payment or Judgment;</P1>
<P1>(d) post-judgment interest at the rate of 14.5% per annum; and</P1>
<P1>(e) the costs of this action on a substantial indemnity basis; and</P1>
<P1>(0 such further and other relief as the Honourable Court may deem just.</P1></P>
<P>2. The Plaintiffs claim is on a Mortgage (&ldquo;Main Mortgage&rdquo;) made between Yao Feng Situ and Yao Jun Situ, as mortgagors and Benson Custodian Corporation as mortgagee, and registered as Instrument No. [#omitted]on May 1, 2017, in the Land Registry Office for the Land Titles Division of Toronto (No. [#omitted]) under which Mortgage the mortgagors mortgaged the lands hereinafter described for a period of six (6) months commencing May 1, 2017 securing the principal sum of $725,000.00 and interest thereon at the rate of 13.99% per annum calculated monthly, not in advance as well after as before maturity and both before and after default. The property is municipally known as [location omitted](hereinafter referred to as the &ldquo;Lewiston Property&rdquo;).</P>
<P>3. The mortgage provides for payment by monthly instalments of $8,452.30 to be paid on the first day of each and every month in each and every year from and including June 1, 2017, and the balance, if any, of the said principal sum and interest shall become due and payable on November 1, 2017.</P>
<P>4. The mortgage was further secured against another property owned by the Defendant, Yao Jun Sit wherein all payments made under one mortgage would be considered to be a payment under the collateral mortgage and default under one mortgage would be considered a default on the other mortgage. The mortgage provided that upon default the mortgagee could at their sole discretion exercise their rights against any or all properties in order to recover all sums due on the mortgage.</P>
<P>[location omitted]</P>
<P>5. The Plaintiff's further claim is on a collateral mortgage made between Yao Jun Situ as mortgagor and Benson Custodian Corporation as mortgagee and registered as Instrument No.[#omitted]on May 1, 2017, in the Land Registry Office for the Land Titles Division of Toronto (No.[#omitted] under the same terms and provisions as the Lewiston Property. The collateral property is municipally known as [location omitted](hereinafter referred to as the &ldquo;Latham Property&rdquo;).</P>
<P>6. Each mortgage provides that the mortgagee may pay all premiums of insurance and all taxes and rates which shall from time to time fall due and be unpaid in respect of the mortgaged premises, and that such payments together with ail costs, charges and expenses which may be incurred in taking, recovering and keeping possession of the said lands, legal fees on solicitor and client basis, and generally in any other proceedings taken in connection with or to realize this security shall be with interest at the rate aforesaid, a charge upon the said lands and any such amounts paid by the mortgagee shall be added to the debt hereby secured and shall be payable forthwith.</P>
<P>7. The taking of a Judgment or Judgments on any of the covenants herein contained shall not operate as a merger of the said covenants or affect the mortgagee's right to interest at the rate and times herein provided.</P>
<P>8. Each mortgage provides that upon default of payment of monies hereby secured or payable, the principal and interest owing shall immediately become due and payable at the option of the mortgagee.</P>
<P>9. Each mortgage provides that on default the mortgagee shall have quiet possession of the said lands free from all encumbrances.</P>
