<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="III">PART III&mdash;ISSUES, LAW AND ARGUMENT</TI>
<BLOCK3><TI>Issues</TI>
<P>10. This motion raises the following issues:
<P1>(a) Is this matter amenable to summary judgment?</P1>
<P1>(b) If so, what is the amount owing under the unredeemed mortgage?</P1>
<P1>(c) Is the plaintiff entitled to possession of the lands as set-out in Schedule &ldquo;A&rdquo;?</P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI>Law</TI>
<BLOCK4><TI><EM>The Test on a Motion for Summary Judgment</EM></TI>
<P>11. A plaintiff may, after the defendant has delivered a statement of defence, move with supporting affidavit material or other evidence for summary judgment. The Court <EM>shall</EM> grant judgment if it is satisfied that there is no genuine issue requiring a trial with respect to the claim.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>, R.R.O. 1990, Reg. 194, Rules 20.01(1) &amp; 20.04(1)(a).</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>12. In light of the Supreme Court of Canada's decision in <CASEREF><SOC>Hryniak v. Mauldin</SOC></CASEREF>, the motion judge without using the new fact-finding powers, determine whether there is a genuine issue requiring a trial based only on the evidence before the Court. There will be no genuine issue requiring a trial when the summary judgment process: &ldquo;(1) allows the judge to make the necessary findings of fact, (1) allows the judge to apply the law to the facts, and (3) is a proportionate, more expeditious and less expensive means to achieve a just result.&rdquo;
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Hryniak v. Mauldin</SOC><CITE>2014 SCC 7</CITE><PARANUM>49 and 66</PARANUM></CASEREF>, <BOLD>Plaintiff's Book of Authorities, Tab 1</BOLD>.</P1></P>
<P>13. In response to affidavit material or other evidence supporting a motion for summary judgment, the defendant may not rest solely on the allegations in the statement of defence but, rather, must set out, in affidavit material or other evidence, specific facts showing that there is a genuine issue requiring a trial. The court will assume that the parties have placed before it, in some form, all of the evidence that will be available for trial.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>, Rule 20.02(2)</BOLD>.</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Sweda Farms Ltd v. Egg Farmers of Ontario</SOC><CITE>2014 ONSC 1200</CITE><PARANUM>33-34</PARANUM><CASEHIST><CASEDISP>affirmed</CASEDISP><CASEREF><CITE>2014 ONCA 878</CITE></CASEREF></CASEHIST></CASEREF><BOLD>, Plaintiff's Book of Authorities, Tabs 2&amp;3.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>14. The standard for fairness to be applied when determining whether the summary judgment process is appropriate in the circumstances is not whether the procedure is as exhaustive as trial, but whether it gives the judge confidence that they can find the necessary facts and apply the relevant legal principles so as to resolve the dispute.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Hryniak v. Mauldin</SOC><CITE>2014 SCC 7</CITE><PARANUM>50</PARANUM></CASEREF>, <BOLD>Plaintiff's Book of Authorities, Tab 1</BOLD>.</P1></P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI>There is no Genuine Issue Requiring a Trial</TI>
<P>15. This matter is suitable for summary judgement. The Court can confidently find the necessary facts and apply the relevant legal principles on the record before it.</P>
<P>16. The statement of defence does not provide a viable defence to statement of clam. The defendants have not provided a responding motion record to assert the substance of their defence as per the court mandated timetable.</P>
<P>17. The defendants may not rest solely on the allegations in the statement of defence but, rather, must set out, in affidavit material or other evidence, specific facts showing that there is a genuine issue requiring a trial. The defendants have failed to do so.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="IV">PART IV&mdash;ORDER SOUGHT</TI>
<P>18. The plaintiff therefore respectfully requests an order as follows:
<P1>(a) summary judgment against the defendants for $631,326.13 plus a per diem of $238.36 multiplied by 196 days between November 1, 2018 to May 13, 2019 (motion date) which equals $46,718.56 in accordance with the Statement of Claim for payment under a mortgage made between the plaintiff and the defendants for a total of $678,044.69;</P1>
<P1>(b) possession of the lands as set-out in motion materials;</P1>
<P1>(c) post-judgment interest at the rate of 14.5% per annum from May 1, 2019 to the date of payment or Judgment;</P1>
<P1>(d) the costs of this action and motion on a substantial indemnity basis.</P1></P>
<P>ALL OF WHICH IS RESPECTFULLY SUBMTTED.</P>
<P>&ellip35; <BOLD>Cary Schneider agent for counsel for the plaintiff</BOLD></P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
