<BLOCK1><TI>FACTUM OF THE DEFENDANTS</TI>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="I">PART I&mdash;OVERVIEW</TI>
<P>1. In this mortgage matter, the Plaintiff refused to renew a mortgage which had been fully up- to-date and then refused to accept ongoing payments from the Defendants commencing November 1, 2018 placing the mortgage in default.</P>
<P>2. The Defendants have replacement financing to replace the outstanding principal and interest of the Plaintiff's mortgage but dispute the entitlement of the Plaintiff to claim a three-month interest penalty and administration fees which are claimed solely based on the Plaintiff's refusal to accept payments.</P>
<P>3. The Defendants further dispute the Plaintiff's entitlement to legal costs in the circumstances.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="II">PART II&mdash;THE FACTS</TI>
<P>4. The Defendants took out a mortgage from the Plaintiff to be secured as against two residential real estate properties in May, 2017. The mortgage was subsequently renewed and came due on November 1, 2018.
<P1><BOLD>Affidavit of Yao Jun Situ, sworn April 26, 2019 [&ldquo;Situ Affidavit&rdquo;] at paras 4-5, page 2 of the Responding Motion Record</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>5. All mortgage payments were made on time during the currency of the Mortgage.
<P1><BOLD>Situ Affidavit at para 5, page 2 of the Responding Motion Record</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>6. Following the renewal date for the mortgage, the Plaintiff refused to accept ongoing payments. The Defendants actively attempted to obtain replacement financing and have now obtained that replacement financing from the Equitable Trust Company.
<P1><BOLD>Situ Affidavit at paras 6-7, page 2 of the Responding Motion Record</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>7. The Defendants dispute the entitlement of the Plaintiff to claim a three -month interest penalty and administrative fees and their legal fees as all of these were generated by the Plaintiff's action in refusing to accept ongoing payments.
<P1><BOLD>Situ Affidavit at paras 10&ndash;12, page 3 of the Responding Motion Record</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="III">PART III&mdash;THE LAW</TI>
<P>8. The mortgage clause under which the Plaintiff claims entitlement to a three-month interest penalty and administrative fees is the following:
<QUOTE><P>Upon default of any payment of any fees due under the mortgage and/or any interest and/or principal secured by the Charge/mortgage the principal amount secured by the Charge/mortgage shall, at the option of the Mortgagee(s), immediately become payable and/or interest under the Charge/mortgage, while in default, shall be calculated at 28% per annum. Upon default of payment of the Principal Due at maturity the balance of the principal and interest secured by the Charge/mortgage shall, at the option of the Mortgagee(s), immediately become due and payable.</P>
<P>The Mortgagee(s) may in writing at any time or times after default of payment of principal, interest, and/or fees due may waive such default and any such waiver shall apply only to the particular default waived and shall not operate as a waiver of any other or future default.</P>
<P>For each Notice of Sale under Mortgage issued by the Mortgagee(s) there shall be an administration charge of Fifteen Hundred Dollar ($1,500.00) payable by the Mortgagor(s) to the Mortgagee(s). In addition of each Statement of Claim under Mortgage issued by the Mortgagee(s) there shall be an additional administration charge of Fifteen Hundred Dollar ($1,500.00) payable by the Mortgagor(s) to the Mortgagee(s). in addition, on the issuing of a Notice of Sale or filing a Statement of Claim, the Mortgagee(s) shall be entitled to collect as liquidated damages from the Mortgagor(s) a sum equal to the payment of three (3) months' interest on the principal amount outstanding. The Mortgagee(s) shall also be entitled to charge a monthly charge equal to any late payment charge provided for in this mortgage from the date of default until the date that the Mortgagor(s) otherwise redeems the mortgage or the date that the property is sold under Power of Sale.</P>
<P>In addition, for each Notice of sale under Mortgage issued by the Mortgagee(s) there shall be a charge of Fifteen Hundred Dollar ($1,500.00) plus GST/HST &amp; Disbursements payable by the Mortgagor(s) to the Mortgagee(s)'s lawyer for the preparation and issuing of the Notice of Sale under Mortgage. For each Statement of Claim under Mortgage issued by the Mortgagee(s) there shall be a charge of Fifteen Hundred Dollar ($1,500.00) plus GST/HST &amp; Disbursements payable by the Mortgagor(s) to the Mortgagee(s)'s lawyer for the preparation and issuing of the Statement of Claim under Mortgage. These fees shall be in addition to any legal fees or other costs associated with the Mortgagee(s) herein asserting its rights under this mortgage upon any default by the Mortgagor(s). the Mortgagor(s) shall also be liable for the Mortgagee(s)'s legal fees, disbursements and GST/HST on a solicitor-client basis for any steps taken after the issuing of the Notice of Sale including but not limited to any negotiations, court applications, eviction proceedings, listing and sale of the property.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>9. It is submitted that the three-month interest penalty clause in this mortgage is similar to the one that was considered by the Court in <CASEREF><SOC>Ialongo v. Serm Investments Limited</SOC></CASEREF> and in <CASEREF><SOC>58 Cardill Inc. v. Rathcliffe Holdings Limited</SOC></CASEREF>.</P>
<P>10. The three-month interest clause is derived from section 17 of the <EM>Mortgages Act</EM> which is intended to provide a remedy to mortgagors in default.</P>
<P>11. In <CASEREF><SOC>Ialongo v. Serm Investments Limited</SOC></CASEREF>, the Court confirmed
<QUOTE><P>the rights afforded by section 17 of the <EM>Mortgages Act</EM> are options made available to the mortgagor on default: it can give notice or pay the bonus prior to the expiry of the notice period. Once, however, the mortgagee takes steps to realize on its security such as by issuing a notice of sale, it cannot convert the rights of the mortgagor under section 17 of the <EM>Mortgages Act</EM> into obligations under the mortgage</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Caroline Luce Ialongo et al. v. Serm Investments Limited</SOC><CITE>2007 CanLii 6242</CITE><COURTJUR>ON SC</COURTJUR></CASEREF> <BOLD>at para 30, page 8 of the Brief of Authorities</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>12. Section 8 of the <EM>Interest Act</EM> provides as follows:
<QUOTE><SEC><N>8.</N><SSEC><N>(1)</N><SSECP>No fine, penalty or rate of interest shall be stipulated for, taken, reserved or exacted on any arrears of principal or interest secured by mortgage on real property .... that has the effect of increasing the charge on the arrears beyond the rate of interest payable on principal money not in arrears.</SSECP></SSEC></SEC></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD><EM>Interest Act</EM>, R.S.C., 1985, c. I-15, section 8</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>13. The Courts have found that a three-month interest penalty does not offend the <EM>Interest Act</EM> where it provides the option to the mortgagor of either providing three-months' notice or paying the three-month interest penalty.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Mastercraft Properties Ltd. et al. v. El Ef Investments Inc.</SOC><CITE>1993 Canlii 8545</CITE><COURTJUR>ON CA</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, <BOLD>pages 16-17 of the Brief of Authorities</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>14. Justice Sanfilippo in <EM>58 Cardill Inc</EM>. noted as follows:
<QUOTE><P>I accept the respondent's submission that the Three-Month Interest Provision does not constitute a penalty or fine, because it requires only the payment of three month's interest when this interest is not paid during the notice period, and is therefore a valid and enforceable mortgage term. This is clear from <CASEREF><SOC>Mastercraft Properties Limited v. EL EF Investments Inc.</SOC><YEAR>1993</YEAR><CITE>14 O.R. (3d) 519</CITE><COURTJUR>Ont. C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, wherein it was determined that a mortgage clause substantively similar if not identical to the Three-Month Interest Provision does not offend s.8 of the <EM>Interest Act</EM>, R.S.C. 1985, c. I&ndash;15, which prohibits that payment of a fine, penalty or rate of interest on arrears of principal or interest that increases the charge on the arrears beyond the rate of interest payable under the mortgage.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>58 <CASEREF><SOC>Cardill Inc. v. Rathcliffe Holdings Limited</SOC><CITE>2017 ONSC 6828</CITE><PARANUM>31</PARANUM></CASEREF>, <BOLD>page 29 of the Brief of Authorities</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>15. Here, however, the mortgagee is refusing to accept payments forcing the Defendants into arrears. Clearly the effect of the three-month interest clause and the administrative fees are to increase the rate of interest on the arrears. They are in the nature of a penalty, which is prohibited under section 8 of the <EM>Interest Act</EM>.</P>
<P>16. It is well-established that the intent of section 8 of the <EM>Interest Act</EM> is to prevent punitive interest on default. The Ontario Court of Appeal has held that the purpose of section 8(1) was to relieve against penalties in any form for default, whether or not any principal not in arrears remains unpaid.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Beauchamp v. Timberland Investment Ltd.</SOC><CITE>1983 Canlii 1816</CITE><COURTJUR>ON CA</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, <BOLD>pages 40-41 of the Brief of Authorities</BOLD></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>P.A.R.C.E.L. Inc. v. Acquaviva</SOC><CITE>2015 ONCA 311 (Canlii)</CITE><PARANUM>48 and 51</PARANUM></CASEREF>, <BOLD>pages 58&ndash;60 of the Brief of Authorities</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>17. It is submitted that in these circumstances where the Defendants have been forced into default by the refusal of the Plaintiff to accept ongoing interest payments that they are not entitled to recover the three-month interest penalty nor the administrative fees they seek to charge.</P>
<P>18. It is further submitted that the Plaintiff should not be entitled to his legal costs given its behaviour in this matter.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="IV">PART IV&mdash;ORDER SOUGHT</TI>
<P>19. The Defendants seek an Order permitting them to pay the outstanding principal and interest due to the Plaintiff, but otherwise requiring the Plaintiff to provide a discharge of mortgage.</P>
<P>20. The Motion of the Plaintiff should be otherwise dismissed with costs to the Defendant.</P>
