<BLOCK1><TI>REPLY FACTUM OF THE PLAINTIFF</TI>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="I">PROCEDURAL ISSUES</TI>
<P>1. By way of a consent court ordered timetable dated March 26, 2019 the parties agreed to a schedule regarding the exchange of materials for the herein summary judgment motion. The defendants were ordered to serve its responding motion record on April 12, 2019 but did not do so until nearly three weeks later on April 30, 2019. The defendants were ordered to serve its responding factum by April 26, 2019 but did not do so until May 6, 2019. The plaintiff submits that the defendants materials should be found inadmissible as they are in breach of a court order.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="II">REPLY TO DEFENDANTS RESPONDING MATERIALS</TI>
<P>2. The Defendants asserted in paragraph 6-7 of the Defendants' affidavit of Yao Jun Situ that they offered a new mortgage to the Plaintiff and that the Plaintiff refused. The Defendants have asserted that they have been actively attempting to obtain replacement financing in order to discharge the mortgage. This is a private mortgage and there is no obligation by the Plaintiff to agree to renew same.</P>
<P>3. In fact, as set-out at paragraph 8 of the Plaintiff's affidavit of Egor Ivandaev, the Plaintiff contacted / reminded the Defendants on four occasions in writing (including a lawyer's letter) before the expiry of the mortgage that the Plaintiff was not willing to renew the mortgage. The defendants were advised that they must payout the mortgage in full on or before November 1, 2018. The defendants failed to do so and are therefore in default.</P>
<P>4. According to the affidavit of Yao Jun Situ at paragraphs 9-10 the Defendants dispute the (a) three month interest amount (b) administrative fees and (c) legal fees. The Defendants have not submitted any law to dispute the administrative fees that are set-out in the mortgage contract as agreed between the parties. The Defendants have not disputed the amount of the legal fees in dispute; only that the Plaintiff should not be entitled to legal fees in general.</P>
<P>5. The Defendants have asserted that Plaintiff is not entitled to three months' worth of interest based on the legal interpretation of section 17 of the <EM>Mortgages Act</EM> (&ldquo;section 17&rdquo;). In particular, they have asserted that section 17 is intended to provide a remedy to mortgagors in default and not primarily for the benefit of the mortgagee. It has been submitted that once the mortgagee takes steps to realize on its security such as by issuing a notice of sale, it cannot convert the rights of the mortgagor under section into obligations under the mortgage.</P>
<P>6. The cases cited by the Defendants to support this proposition all specifically address situations in which the mortgagee is solely relying on section 17 in order to seek relief to obtain the three-month interest obligation. The crux of these decisions is that the mortgagee is not entitled to seek the relief sought specifically under section 17. The decisions relied upon by the Defendants do not address or invalidate the contractual rights as set-out by the parties as it pertains to three months interest clauses. In many of the decisions in which this issue was litigated, there was not a specific provision in the contract that addressed a mortgagee's right to three month's worth of interest upon default of the mortgage. The mortgagee had been relying solely on section 17.</P>
<P>7. The Defendants have asserted that the three-month interest provision in these circumstances would be considered a penalty prohibited under section 8 of the <EM>Interest Act</EM> on the basis that the mortgagee forced the Plaintiffs into arears. The Defendants have agreed that in general that the three-month interest provision does not offend the <EM>Interest Act</EM>.</P>
<P>8. The Defendants have not cited any case law that supports their proposition that the three month interest provision in the herein case violates section 8 the <EM>Interest Act</EM>. The cases cited by the Plaintiffs in their materials address factual scenarios in which it was found that there is an excessive escalation of the interest rate as follows: (a) in <CASEREF><SOC>P.A.R.C.E.L Inc v. Acquaviva</SOC></CASEREF> (2015) the interest rate provided for the escalation of the applicable interest rate from 0.75% to 10% per annum after demand, default, and pre and post judgment (b) in <CASEREF><SOC>Beauchamp v. Timberland</SOC></CASEREF> (1983) the mortgage provided for interest at the rate of 10% until maturity and 20% thereafter.</P>
<P>9. In <CASEREF><SOC>Piesok v. Chessell</SOC></CASEREF> (2016)<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Pieosk v. Chessell</SOC><YEAR>2016</YEAR><CITE>ONSC 1647 (CanLII)</CITE><PARANUM>13&ndash;17</PARANUM></CASEREF></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> the defendants defaulted in a mortgage and the Plaintiffs commenced a claim seeking debt and possession. The defendants took issue with a default/pre-payment charge in the amount of $9,843.75 included on the discharge statement. That sum is based upon the following clause in the Standard Charge Terms under the mortgage:
<QUOTE><P>The Chargor agrees that should this Charge not be discharged on the &ldquo;Balance Due Date&rdquo; or if the Chargor fails to renew/extend this Charge on or before the &ldquo;Balance Due Date&rdquo; together with the applicable renewal/extension fees or if the Chargees commence an action due under any default of the Charge, that the Chargees, in additional to all the revenues available, at their options shall be entitled to charge an additional amount equal to the payment of three months interest on the principal then outstanding.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>10. The court found that the bonus payment is not a &ldquo;fine&rdquo;, &ldquo;penalty&rdquo; or a &ldquo;rate of interest&rdquo; charged on the interest arrears, but rather a payment the mortgagor is required to make for the privilege of retiring the mortgage without providing three months' notice. The court found that the terms of the mortgage are enforceable as it relates the three-month interest charge. There was no violation of section 8 of the <EM>Interest Act</EM> and no finding that there was any violation of section 17 of the <EM>Mortgage Act</EM>. The plaintiffs were found to be entitled to claim the three months' interest payment upon default.</P>
<P>11. Similarly, in <CASEREF><SOC>Piesok v. Johnson</SOC></CASEREF> (2010)<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Piesok v. Johnson</SOC><YEAR>2010</YEAR><CITE>ONSC 1284 (CanLII)</CITE><PARANUM>20&ndash;30</PARANUM></CASEREF></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> the court found a clause in the mortgage contract allowed for the imposition of a charge of three months of interest in the event of realization by the mortgagee.</P>
<P>12. In the Court of Appeal decision of <CASEREF><SOC>1220510 Ontario Inc v. Radium-O</SOC></CASEREF> (2017)<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>1220510 Ontario Inc v. Radium-O</SOC><YEAR>2017</YEAR><CITE>ONCA 490 (Can LII)</CITE></CASEREF></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> the motgagee 1220510 Ontario Inc. lent $6,000,000 to the mortgagor in a vendor take back mortgage. The mortgage matured on May 7, 2016. The appellant had not paid the principal owing and was in default as of that date. The respondent started an application for the appointment of a receiver. After some negotiations, the respondent made a settlement offer for a total amount of $6,162,950.45. This amount included principal, interest, three months' interest compensation, receivership and legal fees, other fees and, taxes. The mortgagor made the payment and thereafter commenced a counter-application seeking to be relieved of paying the three months' interest compensation and receivership costs.</P>
<P>13. As it relates to the three month's interest compensation, an agreement to settle an action is a contract. The Court of Appeal found that there was offer and explicit acceptance. The requirement to pay the three months worth of interest was upheld on the basis of an enforceable contract. While as the <EM>1220510 Ontario Inc</EM> case deals with a contract that was entered into subsequent to the commencement of litigation, the principles remain the same in relation to there herein case. The parties in the case at bar entered into a mortgage contract and one of the terms was that were the mortgagor to default on the contract that &ldquo;the mortgagee shall be entitled to collect as liquidated damages from the Mortgagor(s)'s sum equal to the payment of three (3) months' interest on the principal amount outstanding&rdquo;.</P>
<P>14. Further, in <EM>1220510 Ontario Inc</EM> the mortgagor contended that the motion judge erred by approving the costs and fees relating to the respondent's steps in pursuit of the appointment of a receiver. The mortgagor argued that these cost and fees were in the nature of a penalty and violated section 8 of the <EM>Interest Act</EM>. The Court of Appeal rejected these arguments and found that the steps taken to potentially appoint a receiver were entirely reasonable in light of the appellant's default. The Court of Appeal also found that: &ldquo;And the three month's interest compensation did not violate s. 8 of the <EM>Interest Act</EM>: see <CASEREF><SOC>Master craft Properties Ltd. v. EL EF Investments Inc.</SOC><YEAR>1993</YEAR><CITE>1993 CanLII 8545</CITE><COURTJUR>ON CA</COURTJUR><CASEHIST><CASEREF><CITE>14 O.R. (3d) 519</CITE><COURTJUR>C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF></CASEHIST></CASEREF> and <CASEREF><SOC>Irwin Mintz, In Trust v. Mademont Yonge Inc. and Paul Montgomery</SOC><CITE>2010 ONSC 116 (CanLII)</CITE></CASEREF>.&rdquo;</P>
<P>15. In <CASEREF><SOC>2468390 Ontario Inc v. 5F Investment Group Inc</SOC></CASEREF> (2017)<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>2468390 Ontario Inc v. 5F Investment Group Inc</SOC><YEAR>2017</YEAR><CITE>ONSC 4641 (CanLII)</CITE><PARANUM>27</PARANUM></CASEREF></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> the court set out the competing law as it related to the right of the mortgagee to charge three months' additional interest as claimed in the Notice of Sale, The Court ultimately found that the proper interpretation of section 17 does not permit the mortgagee entitlement to an additional three months' worth of interest once the Notice of Sale has commenced. However, this does prevent the mortgagee having recourse as to the terms of the mortgage. &ldquo;In the present case, and applying the approach taken in <CASEREF><SOC>Ialongo v. Serm Investments Ltd.</SOC></CASEREF>, once the Defendants issued their Notice of Sale they could rely only on the remedies set out in the mortgage and not on any additional &ldquo;bonus interest&rdquo; said to be owing under s. 17 of the [Mortgage] <EM>Act</EM>.&rdquo;</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="III">PART IV&mdash;ORDER SOUGHT</TI>
<P>16. The plaintiff therefore respectfully requests an order as follows:
<P1>(a) summary judgment against the defendants for $631,326.13 plus a per diem of $238.36 multiplied by 196 days between November 1, 2018 to May 13, 2019 (motion date) which equals $46,718.56 in accordance with the Statement of Claim for payment under a mortgage made between the plaintiff and the defendants for a total of $678,044.69;</P1>
<P1>(b) possession of the lands as set-out in motion materials;</P1>
<P1>(c) post-judgment interest at the rate of 14.5% per annum from May 1, 2019 to the date of payment or Judgment;</P1>
<P1>(d) the costs of this action and motion on a substantial indemnity basis.</P1></P>
<P>ALL OF WHICH IS RESPECTFULLY SUBMITTED</P>
<P>&ellip35; <BOLD>Cary Schneider agent for counsel for the plaintiff</BOLD></P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
